male":"1490–Overleden","1415–1503":"1415–1503","1424–Female":"1424–Overleden","Bef 8 September 1527":"vóór 8 september 1527","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","10 January 1474":"10 januari 1474","11 January 1510":"11 januari 1510","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1446":"1446","1424":"1424","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","about 1468":"circa 1468","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1474":"1474","about 1466":"circa 1466","about 1475":"circa 1475","1527":"1527","about 1472":"circa 1472","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England"},"en":{"1446–Bef 8 September 1527":"1446–before 8 September 1527","1446–1527":"1446–1527","1466–Female":"1466–Deceased","1468–Female":"1468–Deceased","1472–Female":"1472–Deceased","1474–1510":"1474–1510","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","1415–1503":"1415–1503","1424–Female":"1424–Deceased","Bef 8 September 1527":"before 8 September 1527","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","10 January 1474":"10 January 1474","11 January 1510":"11 January 1510","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1446":"1446","1424":"1424","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1466":"1466","about 1468":"about 1468","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1474":"1474","about 1466":"about 1466","about 1475":"about 1475","1527":"1527","about 1472":"about 1472","Brenchley, Kent, England":"Brenchley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Downer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Isle of Wight, Hampshire, and Sussex): topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or down, from Middle English <i>douner</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>doun</i> (Old English <i>dūn</i>) ‘hill’ + <i>-er</i>. It is synonymous with <i>atte Doune</i> (see   Down  ) and is a type of formation especially common in Sussex, Surrey, and Hampshire.","English: in the north-West Midlands perhaps a variant of <b>Downward</b> with shortening of the final syllable to <i>-er</i>, a habitational name probably from Downwood (Herefordshire) and perhaps also Dunwood (Staffordshire), with <i>-wood</i> re-etymologized as <i>-ward</i> and occasionally shortened to <i>-ard</i>. See also   Downard  .","Irish (Tipperary): variant of   Dooner   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunman","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Downman</b>, a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) down’; compare   Downer  . Alternatively, in some instances the name may be a late variant of   Downham  ."]},{"name":"Down","meanings":["English (Devon): topographic name for someone who lived on or near a down or low hill, from Middle English <i>dun(e)</i>, <i>doun(e)</i> (Old English <i>dūn</i>) ‘down, low hill’. See also   Downer  .","English (Devon): possibly in some cases a patronymic from the Old English personal name <i>Dūn</i>, but later names of this origin cannot reliably be distinguished from those originating from the topographic sense. See   Dunn   2."]},{"name":"Downard","meanings":["English: variant of   Downer  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>. <i>Downard</i> was re-etymologized as <i>Downeherd</i> and <i>Downward</i>, and perhaps also as <i>Dunwood</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":9,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"